  "target_response": {
    "text": "HRV is heart rate variability — the tiny differences in timing between one heartbeat and the next. Counterintuitively, more variability is generally the good sign: when your nervous system is rested and balanced, beat-to-beat timing fluctuates freely, and when you're run down from hard training, poor sleep, illness, or stress, the rhythm gets more metronome-like and HRV drops. That's why trackers use it as a recovery signal. Two honest caveats: it's only meaningful against your own baseline, since normal values vary hugely between people, and single days are noisy — trends over weeks are what count. In your case there's no HRV to look at, because manual logging has no sensor measuring it overnight; your log currently shows sleep, like last night's 6.7 h. If you ever want the metric itself, that takes a wearable.",
